From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: GE-Proton <git@localhost>
Date: Tue, 21 Jul 2026 21:45:00 -0600
Subject: [PATCH] sechost: Order Sony HID arrival after speaker publication.

A hotplugged USB Sony controller publishes its HID interface before
PipeWire/Pulse has reported the matching controller speaker and mmdevapi
has completed its AudioEndpoint update. Applications which associate the
controller with its speaker during that first HID arrival can therefore
miss the speaker for the lifetime of the connection.

Do not repair that race by fabricating a HID remove/arrival pair after the
fact. Replaying the HID lifecycle tears down live application controller
objects and can make managed audio code activate the new endpoint through
an object of the old type.

Instead, hold the original USB Sony HID arrival in sechost, keyed by the
device container ID. Once mmdevapi has completed endpoint publication and
sent the matching endpoint notifications, signal sechost to deliver that
original arrival exactly once. Continue processing unrelated PnP events
while it is pending, cancel it if the physical HID is removed, and use a
bounded timeout so HID input remains available if no controller speaker is
reported.

Remove the delayed synthetic MMDevice replug notifications; endpoint
publication and HID arrival now have a deterministic order without
inventing either endpoint or HID lifecycles. No controller state is kept
after the pending arrival is delivered or cancelled.

